# Proposed Microservices Architecture

**Domain-driven design with autonomous service boundaries**

<<mermaid>>
  flowchart TD
      A[API Gateway] --> B[User Service]
      A --> C[Product Service]
      A --> D[Order Service]
      A --> E[Payment Service]
      A --> F[Inventory Service]
      A --> G[Notification Service]
      
      B --> H[(User DB)]
      C --> I[(Product DB)]
      D --> J[(Order DB)]
      E --> K[(Payment DB)]
      F --> L[(Inventory DB)]
      
      M[Event Bus] --> B
      M --> C
      M --> D
      M --> E
      M --> F
      M --> G
      
      style A fill:#2196f3,color:#fff
      style M fill:#4caf50,color:#fff

**{{services_count}} microservices organized into 7 domain boundaries**

@notes:
- API Gateway provides unified entry point and security
- Each service owns its data and business logic
- Event-driven communication enables loose coupling
- Domain boundaries align with business capabilities

---

# Service Decomposition Strategy

**Systematic breakdown of monolithic domains**

| Domain | Current Lines of Code | Target Services | Complexity |
|--------|----------------------|-----------------|------------|
| **User Management** | 85K | 3 services | Medium |
| **Product Catalog** | 120K | 8 services | High |
| **Order Processing** | 95K | 6 services | High |
| **Payment Processing** | 45K | 4 services | Medium |
| **Inventory Management** | 65K | 5 services | Medium |
| **Analytics & Reporting** | 75K | 12 services | Low |
| **Notifications** | 35K | 3 services | Low |

**Decomposition prioritized by business value and technical risk**

@notes:
- Lines of code indicate complexity and effort
- High complexity domains require careful planning
- Service count based on bounded context analysis
- Prioritization balances quick wins with strategic value

---

# Technology Stack Selection

**Cloud-native technologies optimized for microservices**

::: success
**Core Technologies:**
- **Container Platform:** Kubernetes on AWS EKS
- **Service Mesh:** Istio for traffic management
- **API Gateway:** Kong for unified API management
- **Event Streaming:** Apache Kafka for async communication
- **Monitoring:** Prometheus + Grafana + Jaeger
- **CI/CD:** GitLab CI with automated testing
:::

**Language Strategy:** Polyglot approach (Java, Go, Python, Node.js)

@notes:
- Kubernetes provides container orchestration and scaling
- Istio enables advanced traffic management and security
- Kong offers enterprise-grade API management
- Kafka ensures reliable event streaming
- Polyglot approach optimizes for service requirements

---

# Data Architecture and Management

**Distributed data management with consistency guarantees**

<<mermaid>>
  flowchart LR
      A[Application Layer] --> B[Service Layer]
      B --> C[Data Access Layer]
      C --> D[Primary Databases]
      C --> E[Read Replicas]
      C --> F[Caching Layer]
      
      G[Event Sourcing] --> H[Event Store]
      H --> I[Projections]
      
      J[Data Pipeline] --> K[Analytics DB]
      
      style D fill:#4caf50,color:#fff
      style H fill:#ff9800,color:#fff
      style K fill:#9c27b0,color:#fff

**Database per service pattern with eventual consistency**

@notes:
- Each service manages its own data
- Read replicas improve query performance
- Caching reduces database load
- Event sourcing provides audit trail and recovery
- Analytics database supports business intelligence

---

# Migration Strategy and Phases

**Strangler Fig pattern for gradual migration**

| Phase | Duration | Services Migrated | Risk Level |
|-------|----------|-------------------|------------|
| **Phase 1** | 2 months | User Management (3) | Low |
| **Phase 2** | 2 months | Notifications (3) | Low |
| **Phase 3** | 2 months | Analytics (12) | Medium |
| **Phase 4** | 1 month | Inventory (5) | Medium |
| **Phase 5** | 3 months | Payment (4) | High |
| **Phase 6** | 4 months | Product + Orders (14) | High |

**Total timeline: {{migration_timeline}} with parallel development**

@notes:
- Strangler Fig allows gradual replacement
- Low-risk services first to build confidence
- High-risk services require more careful planning
- Parallel development maintains feature velocity

---

